# Inception-of-Things — Detailed Project Guide


## Why this project?

The project is a hands-on introduction to **Kubernetes** — a system for running and managing containerised applications. When you have many applications that need to scale, update without downtime, and restart on failure, Kubernetes handles all of that.

But Kubernetes is complex. That's why the project is built **incrementally**: each part adds one new concept and one new tool.

```
Part 1: Virtual machines → two-node cluster (basic setup)
   ↓
Part 2: One VM → three apps → hostname-based routing
   ↓
Part 3: Containers instead of VMs → automatic updates from GitHub
   ↓
Bonus:  Same thing, but the Git server also lives inside the cluster (full autonomy)
```

The parts are **independent** — you can run any one of them without the others.

---

## Host preparation

Before running anything, you need to install the required tools.

**Universal script:** [setup_host.sh](setup_host.sh) — installs everything needed for all parts at once:
- `libvirt` + `QEMU/KVM` — virtualisation engine (for Parts 1 and 2)
- `Vagrant` + `vagrant-libvirt` plugin — VM management (for Parts 1 and 2)
- `Docker` — container engine (for Parts 3 and Bonus)
- `K3d` — Kubernetes cluster inside Docker (for Parts 3 and Bonus)
- `kubectl` — Kubernetes CLI (everywhere)
- `Helm` — Kubernetes package manager (for the Bonus)

```bash
bash setup_host.sh
# After it finishes: log out and back in (to apply Docker/libvirt group membership)
```

Each part also has its own setup script if you only need that part:
[p1/setup-host.sh](p1/setup-host.sh) · [p3/setup_host.sh](p3/setup_host.sh) · [bonus/setup_host.sh](bonus/setup_host.sh)

