## Part 2 — One VM, three apps, smart routing

**Directory:** [p2/](p2/) · **Detailed README:** [p2/README.md](p2/README.md)

### The idea

We take one VM running Kubernetes and deploy **three different web applications** on it. All three run on the same IP and the same port 80 — but Kubernetes knows which one to send a request to by looking at the `Host` header (the site name in the browser).

The new tool here is **Ingress** and **Traefik** — a smart reverse proxy inside the cluster.

```
Request for app1.com → App 1
Request for app2.com → App 2
Request for anything else → App 3
```

### Components and files

#### VM and K3s

One virtual machine `urosbyS` (`192.168.56.110`), defined in [p2/Vagrantfile](p2/Vagrantfile). Created via Vagrant + libvirt, same as Part 1.

Provisioning script [p2/scripts/setup.sh](p2/scripts/setup.sh):
1. Installs K3s
2. Waits for K3s and Traefik to be fully ready
3. Applies all Kubernetes manifests from the `confs/` directory

#### Three applications

Each application is a set of three Kubernetes objects in a single file:

**Application 1** → [p2/confs/app1.yaml](p2/confs/app1.yaml)
**Application 2** → [p2/confs/app2.yaml](p2/confs/app2.yaml)
**Application 3** → [p2/confs/app3.yaml](p2/confs/app3.yaml)

Each file contains:

| Object | What it is | Why it's needed |
|--------|-----------|-----------------|
| **Deployment** | Specification: which container to run, how many replicas | Kubernetes knows what to keep alive and how many |
| **Service** | A stable "address" inside the cluster | Allows reaching the app by name rather than pod IP |
| **ConfigMap** | Stores the HTML page served by nginx | A way to pass config/content to the container without rebuilding the image |

All three apps use the `nginx:alpine` image — a lightweight web server. They differ only in HTML content (from the ConfigMap) and replica count:
- App 1: 1 replica
- App 2: **3 replicas** (demonstrating scaling)
- App 3: 1 replica (the default catch-all)

#### Traefik Ingress — smart router

**Traefik** is the Ingress Controller built into K3s. It listens on external port 80 and, when it receives an HTTP request, inspects the `Host` header to determine where to forward it.

Routing rules are defined in [p2/confs/ingress.yaml](p2/confs/ingress.yaml):

```
Host: app1.com  →  Service: app1-service (→ App 1 pods)
Host: app2.com  →  Service: app2-service (→ App 2 pods)
(no rule)       →  Service: app3-service (→ App 3, default backend)
```

#### /etc/hosts — local domain resolution

The browser doesn't know that `app1.com` resolves to `192.168.56.110`. For this to work on the host machine, the Makefile automatically adds a line to `/etc/hosts`:

```
192.168.56.110  app1.com app2.com app3.com
```

Done via `make update-hosts` — without this, the domains won't resolve.

### How the components interact

```
   Browser / curl on host
          │
          │ curl http://app1.com  (resolves to 192.168.56.110 via /etc/hosts)
          ▼
   ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
   │  VM: urosbyS (192.168.56.110)                                   │
   │                                                                 │
   │  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐   │
   │  │  K3s (Kubernetes)                                        │   │
   │  │                                                          │   │
   │  │  [port 80]                                               │   │
   │  │      │                                                   │   │
   │  │      ▼                                                   │   │
   │  │  Traefik (Ingress Controller)                            │   │
   │  │  inspects the Host header                                │   │
   │  │      │                                                   │   │
   │  │   ┌──┴──────────────────────────────┐                   │   │
   │  │   │                                 │                   │   │
   │  │   ▼ Host=app1.com   ▼ Host=app2.com │ everything else   │   │
   │  │  app1-service      app2-service     ▼                   │   │
   │  │       │                 │      app3-service             │   │
   │  │       ▼                 ▼           │                   │   │
   │  │  [Pod: App1]   [Pod: App2 ×3]  [Pod: App3]             │   │
   │  │  nginx:alpine   nginx:alpine    nginx:alpine            │   │
   │  │  HTML from      HTML from       HTML from               │   │
   │  │  ConfigMap      ConfigMap       ConfigMap               │   │
   │  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │
   └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Running

```bash
cd p2
make up      # create VM, start K3s, deploy applications
make test    # check HTTP responses from all three apps
make check   # view Ingress, services, pod status
make destroy # tear everything down
```

Tests in [p2/test.sh](p2/test.sh) verify: all three domains resolve, all three return HTTP 200, deployments exist, Ingress is configured.

